<head>NIGHT</head><list type="altnames">
<item>NIGHTTIME</item>
<item>HOURS OF DARKNESS</item>
<item>DARKNESS</item>
<item>DARK</item>
<item>NIGHTFALL</item>
<item>SUNSET</item></list><list type="translations"><item xml:lang="zh">夜裡</item><item xml:lang="och">夜</item></list>
<div type="definition">
<p>PART of DAY when it is COMPLETELY DARK AND when one SLEEPS.</p></div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. Yè 夜 (ant. zhòu 晝 "daytime", and rì 日 "day (when it is bright)") is the general term referring to the part of the day when it is dark, i.e. the evening and the night.</p>
<p>2. Xiāo 宵 (ant. zhòu 晝 ) refers to the night only, without including the evening, and the reference is not to the length of time so much as to the absence of sunlight.</p>
<p>3. Yè fēn 夜分 (ant. rì zhōng 日中 "midday") refers to midnight.</p>
<p>4. Sù 宿 refers to a night as what is spent in a hostel, or as the time one uses for sleep.</p>
<p>5. Míng 冥 is occasionally used to refer, by synecdoche, to the night as the time when it is dark.</p></div>
